3. Analysis 
 
As the dependent variable is a count variable (the number of lethal force incidents), we make use of count-based regression modelling strategies. Standard Poisson and negative binomial regression approaches were deemed inappropriate, given the repeated measures nature of our data in that agencies were examined up to 4 years each. In addition, preliminary analyses suggested substantial overdispersion. As a result, our primary analyses make use of multi-level mixed effects negative binomial regression models estimated using the glmmTMB package in R ( Brooks et al., 2017 ). For each of these models, we include the natural logarithm of the population of the city as an offset variable to account for population differences. 
 
First, we estimate two mixed-effects negative binomial regression models using the raw (uncleaned) 1033 and FE data. The first of these models uses the logged USD value of all 1033 acquisitions as the primary measure of militarization, while the second model uses the sum of all 1033 acquisitions as the primary measure of militarization. Next, we estimate these models again using cleaned 1033 and FE data, as well as an additional model where the value of acquisitions does not include military vehicles. Lastly, we estimate these models disaggregated by agency size. Prior research indicates that predictors of lethal force vary by agency size ( Willits & Nowacki, 2014 ). Therefore, this disaggregation operates both as a robustness check for the models described above and as further examination of the differences between small and large agencies. Smaller agencies are those defined as serving fewer than 100,000 people, while large agencies cover populations over 100,000. Given the relative sparseness of lethal force incidents in smaller cities, lethal force is dichotomized for these models (both as the outcome variable and as the lagged measure of lethal force), which are then analyzed as mixed-effect logistic regression models. We also discuss a number of additional robustness checks that were performed that are available upon request. 
4. Results 
 
Table two presents the first four mixed-effects negative binomial regression models. Models 1 and 2 (the raw models) make use of all 1033 and FE data, while models 3 and 4 make use of only the cleaned versions of these data. 
 
Model 1 shows that the logged value of 1033 acquisitions was significantly related to police lethal force. As shown in this first column, 1033 acquisitions were negatively related to police lethal force ( b  = −0.015, p  < .05, Incident Rate Ratio =  e .=0.015  = 0.985), suggesting that police agencies which obtain 1033 items of greater USD value in the prior year are less likely to use lethal force than other agencies, a result similar to the findings of Bove and Gavrilova (2017) and Harris and colleagues (2018). Model 2 reveals that the number of 1033 acquisitions obtained in the prior year is not significantly related to police lethal force, indicating that dollar value and number of items do not present the same results. 
 
In terms of control variables, the lagged FE measure is positively and significantly related to lethal force incidents in Models 1 and 2, suggesting that agencies which used greater numbers of lethal force more in the past year were also more likely to use lethal force in the current year. Similarly, the violent crime rate is also positively related to lethal force incidents in both models, indicating that agencies in cities with higher crime rates are likely to have greater numbers of lethal force incidents. Median income and the percentage of the population which graduated from high school or higher are significant protective factors in both models, suggesting that police use lethal force at lower rates in cities with higher median incomes and with larger educated populations. Conversely, the percentage of the population which is Black is positively and significantly related to lethal police force in these first two models. Lastly, agency size was inversely and significantly related to police lethal force. This indicates that controlling for other factors (including the population of the city, which is included as offset variable), larger agencies were less likely to use lethal force than other agencies. 
 
The results for the cleaned models (Models 3 and 4 in Table 2 ) are substantively different in regards to police militarization. Once cleaned, the USD value is no longer significantly related to related to police lethal force. The number of 1033 acquisitions (cleaned), however, is positively related to use of force, indicating that agencies which obtained more items were likely to have more lethal force incidents than other agencies. Importantly, this result runs contrary to the results of the model using uncleaned data. The model indicates no difference between measures based on overall value of militaristic items and the value of militaristic items minus vehicles (Models 3 and 5). 
 
